<dl style="margin-left: 2 em">
 
<a name="anchor"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">ANCHOR(S)</dt> 
  <dd>The device (or devices) for securing a vessel when moored in a roadstead 
  or harbour and not alongside a wharf or quay � but see the note below, �<a href="#anchorflag">anchor flag</a>� and
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvf6.html#fouledanchor">fouled anchor)</a>&rsquo;.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4224.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4224.gif" alt="[anchor]" border="0" height="108"/></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4225.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4225.gif" alt="[anchor]" border="0" height="108"/></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4226.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4226.gif" alt="[anchor]" border="0" height="108"/></a><br />
  <em>Flag of the <a href="gb-lha.html#lha">Lord High Admiral 1661</a>, England (fotw);	
  Flag of the <a href="gb-lha.html#ab75">Admiralty Board 1976 � 2003</a>, UK (fotw); 
  Pennant of the <a href="it~navy.html#pol">State Police Nautical Squad</a>, Italy (fotw) </em>
  <p>
  <em>Notes<br>
  a) Whilst other orientations are known, anchors are usually (but not invariably) illustrated 
  vertically with the ring uppermost, and:<br>
  b) In a traditional anchor (as it is generally seen on flags) the chief parts are the shank or main 
  section, the ring to which its cable or chain may be attached, the stock or cross piece below that 
  ring, the arms at the base and the flukes at each end of those arms. 
</em> </dd>

<hr />
  <a name="anchorcross"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">ANCHOR CROSS</dt>
  <dd>In heraldry see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvcr.html#crossmoline">cross moline</a>&rsquo;.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3060.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3060.gif" alt="[example]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br /><em>Flag of <a href="nl-zh-og.html">Oegstgeest</a>, The Netherlands 
  (fotw)</em></dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="anchorflag"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">ANCHOR FLAG</dt>
  <dd>1) In UK usage, a term for the flag of the Lord High Admiral, and one the three 
  masthead flags flown (since c1660) when the monarch is aboard a naval vessel  � 
  the Lord High Admiral&rsquo;s flag (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvm1.html#mastheadflag">masthead flag</a>&rsquo;).<br>2) 
  In UK usage, now obsolete, the flag of the Board of Admiralty - the admiralty 
  flag - but see note a) below (also �<a href="vxt-dvf6.html#fouledanchor">fouled anchor</a>�).
  <p><a href="../images/v/vxt-d1984.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1984.gif" alt="[Lord High Admiral]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d933b.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d933b.gif" alt="[Lord High Admiral]" border="0" width="216" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d933c.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d933c.gif" alt="[Lord High Admiral]" border="0" width="216" height="108" /></a>
  <br> 
  <em>Lord High Admiral 
  <a href="gb-lha.html#jas2">1685 � 1688</a>, England (fotw); The Board of Admiralty 
  <a href="gb-lha.html#land">19th Century</a>, UK (fotw); 
  and as <a href="gb-lha.html#1929">modified in 1929</a>, UK (fotw) 
  </em> 
  <p><em>Notes<br>a) The Board of Admiralty was dissolved in 1964 with the office of Lord High Admiral reverting to the crown,
however, during the preceding two hundred and fifty years the role was most often �in commission� and the
anchor flag also flown by the Board.<br>b) The three masthead flags flown 
  (since c. 1660) when the monarch is 
  aboard a naval vessel are that of the Lord High Admiral at the 
  fore, the royal standard at the main and a union jack at the mizzen (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-l.html#launchingflags">launching flags</a>&rsquo; and 
  its second note following (also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvf6.html#foremast">foremast</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-m.html#main">main</a>&rsquo; 
  and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvm3.html#mizzen">mizzen</a>&rsquo;).</em>
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3660.jpg">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3660.jpg" alt="[Anchor flag]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br><em>A Royal Visit to the Fleet 1672, William van de Veld (NMM)</em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="ancient"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">ANCIENT</dt>
  <dd>1) In heraldry, a coat of arms or charge formerly in use but now replaced 
  by another design which is then termed modern such as, for example, Austria ancient 
  and Austria modern � see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvm4.html#modern">modern</a>&rsquo;.</dd>
  <dd>2) In vexillology, a 16th/17th Century term, now wholly obsolete, for a ship&rsquo;s stern mounted 
  ensign, or military colour whether displayed ashore or afloat - an anshent or auncient (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc5.html#color">colour 2)</a>&rsquo;,
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-d.html#deckflags">deck flags)</a>&rsquo;),
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dve2.html#ensign">ensign 1)</a>&rsquo;,
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvp1.html#pavisade">pavisade</a>&rsquo;, and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvsb.html#streamer">streamer 2)</a>&rsquo;.</dd>
  <dd>3) A 16th/17th Century term, now wholly obsolete, equivalent to, and with 
  the same duties as, the later but also obsolete army rank of ensign (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dve2.html#ensign">ensign 3)</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dve2.html#ensign">ensign 4)</a>&rsquo;).
  <p>&nbsp;<a href="../images/v/vxt-d1826a.gif"><img src="../images/v/vxt-d1826a.gif" alt="[ancient example]" border="0" height="108" /></a> 
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1826b.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1826b.gif" alt="[modern example]" border="0" height="108" /></a> 
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4510.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4510.gif" alt="[English 1590 example]" border="0" height="108" /></a><br />
  <em>France 
  <a href="fr_mon.html#anc">Ancient</a>, France <a href="fr_mon.html#thr">Modern</a> (fotw); 
  <a href="gb~tudor.html#his">Ancient/Ship&rsquo;s Ensign, English c1590</a> 
  (fotw)  </em>
  </dd>
 
  <hr /><a name="ancientcrown"></a>
