  <em>Arms and Flag of <a href="pt-stsrg.html">Reguenga</a>, Portugal (fotw)</em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="ancientship"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">ANCIENT SHIP</dt> 
  <dd>In English heraldry the term for a (usually but not invariably) single-masted sailing ship, regardless of specific type � an antique ship � but see notes 
  below (also �<a href="vxt-dvl4.html#lymphad">lymphad</a>�).<p>
    <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2601.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2601.gif" alt="[ancient ship]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
    <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2794a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2794a.gif" alt="[ancient ship]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
    <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3839.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3839.gif" alt="[ancient ship]" border="0" height="108" /></a>&nbsp;
  <br>
  <em>Flag of <a href="hr-ri-ko.html">Kostrena</a>, Croatia (fotw); 
	Arms of 
	<a href="pt-lsb.html">Lisboa</a>, Portugal (fotw); Flag of <a href="de-wim.html">Wittmund</a>, Germany (fotw)</em> 
  <p>
  <em>Notes</em>
  <em><br>a) A vessel with oars but more than one mast should be blazoned �galley� � see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-g.html#galley">galley</a>&rsquo;.<br>
  b) Single-masted Medieval sailing ships fall into a number of different categories of which two are separately defined herein under &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc4.html#cog">cog 2)</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvn2.html#nef">nef</a>&rsquo;.<br>
  c) This term can (and sometimes does) include sailing vessels with more than one mast as illustrated below � see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc2.html#caravel">caravel</a>&rsquo;, &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc2.html#carrack">carrack</a>&rsquo; and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-g.html#galleon">galleon</a>&rsquo;.
		</em>
  <dd><p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4339.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4339.gif" alt="[ancient ship]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br /><em>Flag of <a href="ru-47-lo.html">Lodyeynoye Polye</a>, Russia (fotw)</em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="andiron"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">ANDIRON</dt> 
  <dd>A device, usually made of cast iron, used to hold logs safely within a fireplace - in 
  Continental heraldry it is often stylized in the form of pall (or Y-shape) with ornamented 
  endings and details as illustrated below (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc2.html#carbuncle">carbuncle</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvf6.html#forkedcross">forked cross</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvm3.html#millrind">millrind</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-p.html#pall">pall</a>&rsquo;).  
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4460.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4460.gif" alt="[andiron]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4461.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4461.gif" alt="[andiron]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4462.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4462.gif" alt="[andiron]" border="0" height="108" /></a>&nbsp;
  <br /><em>Arms of
  <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sulzfeld,_Baden-W�rttemberg">Sulzfeld</a>,
  <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saal_an_der_Saale">Saal upon Saale</a> 
  and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gro�bardorf">Gro�bardorf</a>, 
  Germany (Wikipedia)</em>.
    
