  <hr /><a name="applique"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">APPLIQU&#201; </dt>
  <dd>(n &amp; v) A method of flag manufacture in which one or more pieces of cloth 
  are stitched on the field to form a design. This technique is often used where 
  the design on the obverse differs from that on the reverse � but see 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvd4.html#doubleapplique">double appliqu&#233;</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs4.html#singleapplique">single appliqu&#233;</a>&rsquo; (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-o.html#obverse">obverse</a>&rsquo; 
  and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvr2.html#reverse">reverse</a>&rsquo;).
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="appointmentflag"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">APPOINTMENT FLAG </dt>
  <dd>1) In UK and some other military usage, that flag which corresponds to a particular 
  position held, rather than to the rank of the officer who currently holds it - 
  but see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvp5.html#positional">positional flag</a>&rsquo; 
  (also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc4.html#classflag">class flag</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-r.html#rankflag">rank flag 1)</a>&rsquo;).</dd>
  <dd>2) See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvd3.html#distinguishingflag">distinguishing flag 1</a>)&rsquo;.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1599.gif">
